# Checkpoints — canonical process (mandatory)

When the user asks to **set / create / record a checkpoint** (any phrasing: “checkpoint here”, milestone snapshot, named git tag, etc.), treat it as **one workflow**. Do **not** stop after only a narrative file or only a tag.

## Triggers

Phrases include: “set a checkpoint”, “create a checkpoint”, “checkpoint here”, “record a checkpoint”, “add a checkpoint”, “new checkpoint”.

## Steps (complete all before finishing)

1. **Read** **`Documentation/checkpoints.md`** (“How Checkpoints Work” + **Checkpoints** table) so the process matches the repo.
2. **Snapshot commit** — Prefer a dedicated commit that includes the registry update and optional `Documentation/checkpoint-<slug>.md`. If the user wants the tag on existing `HEAD`, use that commit’s full hash.
3. **Registry row** — Append **one row** to the **Checkpoints** table: **Name**, **Tag**, **Commit** (full hash), **Created (IST)** (use tag creation time or commit time in `+05:30` form, consistent with existing rows), **TODOs** (numbered or lettered; mirror tag/commit message if used).
4. **Annotated tag** — `git tag -a checkpoint/<slug> <commit> -m "..."` (or legacy name if required); tag must appear in the table.
5. **Optional narrative** — `Documentation/checkpoint-<slug>.md` may supplement the row; it **must** state that the checkpoint is listed in **`checkpoints.md`** and repeat tag + commit + IST (see existing examples).
6. **Commit** — Stage and commit `Documentation/checkpoints.md` and any new/updated `checkpoint-*.md` (follow-up registry-only commit is allowed if the snapshot commit already landed without the row—see **`checkpoints.md`**).

**Forbidden as “done” alone:** only `Documentation/checkpoint-*.md`, or only a git tag, or only Cursor todos, without a **Checkpoints** table row.

## After setting the checkpoint (playback — mandatory)

Before ending the reply, **read** the **Checkpoints** table from **`Documentation/checkpoints.md`** (after your edits) and **print the full list** for the user:

- For **each** row: **name**, **Commit** (full git object id from the **Commit** column), **Created (IST)** date/time, and **TODOs** (the whole cell).

Format as a clear markdown list or table so the user can scan every checkpoint in one place. This confirms registration and avoids “invisible” checkpoints.

